    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-04-29T15:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-04-29T15:10:00-05:00" n="168"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d168">
                <head>168. Memorandum From the President’s Special Assistant (<persName type="from"
                        >Rostow</persName>) to President <persName type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d168fn1">Source: Johnson Library, White House
                        Central Files, Confidential File, FG 11–5. Confidential. Copies were sent to
                            <persName corresp="#p_MBD1">Moyers</persName> and Kintner.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-04-29T16:10:00-04:00">April 29, 1966, 4:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>General <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> made a reference<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d168fn2">Not further identified.</note> to our lack of use of
                    the formal <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> machinery. It could be picked up
                    this year as a political issue. One way to head it off would be to budget for a
                    few formal sessions. My first suggestion is: a formal <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> session on Vietnam at the end of Lodge’s visit, when all the
                    major issues are settled between us and we can control what matters do and don’t
                    get into play.<note n="3" xml:id="d168fn3">An <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> meeting on Vietnam, in which Lodge participated, was held
                        on May 10. Lodge returned to Washington for consultations in early May and
                        departed May 17.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">W.W. Rostow</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="4" xml:id="d168fn4">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
